>The biggest watchouts I'd see off the hop would be keeping the mom's exhibitionism from going too over the top too fast
Yeen stepmom will be the story's protag'; her degeneration is gradual, but not something that's evading her self-awareness. The focal points of her descent are hallmarks of her character, her adherence to her principles, and, most crucially, her role as a mother. What transpires is absolutely unprecedented to her. She's not aware she's capable of what she allows to happen. She's the sort of person that belongs to a sheltered community, say a church, sees things happen to people, and takes comfort, at a deep, barely-conscious level, that that couldn't possibly happen to her. But, by choice, she's lonely; she adopts a child, say aged two/three, and takes to motherhood well. I'm big on tantalizing this sort of character progression, but not without a chance at redemption. Just know, the further she goes, the more out of control and uncomfortable with herself she becomes.

She loves her child - but things change when he becomes a young man. He rebels, he refers her by name, and he dissociates from her in ways not uncommon for teenage orphans. She takes her control of their home and their lives for granted, she loses touch with the importance of her agency as guardian and parent partly because he's on the cusp of legally-defined adulthood and because they aren't blood-related (a vulnerability). She allows him to make choices and treat her in a way that snicks and pieces away the columns upon which rests the nature and sanctity of their relationship. What's left when that fails are individuals: a horny and lonely woman and a thrice-horny and needy young man. I'm still working out the "redemption" part, but the drama and the hard fall are pretty well defined in my mind's eye.
